<section class="section faq-section section-alt-bg">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="accordion">
            <h3 class="accordion-category-heading">Installation &amp; Refurbished Projects</h3>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <button class="accordion-header" aria-expanded="false">
                    What is the process for a system upgrade?
                    <span class="accordion-icon"></span>
                </button>
                <div class="accordion-content">
                    <p>
                        Our upgrade packages offer a cost-effective solution to gauge obsolescence by reusing existing measuring frames,
                        sensors, and cabling. This minimizes installation costs and downtime, with most upgrades completed in just a few days.
                        The process starts with a full evaluation of your current system to see what can be retrofitted with the latest technology.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <button class="accordion-header" aria-expanded="false">
                    Are your components compatible with older systems?
                    <span class="accordion-icon"></span>
                </button>
                <div class="accordion-content">
                    <p>
                        Yes. Our x-ray sources and detectors are mechanically and electrically backwards compatible with those used in many older gauges,
                        including systems from DMC and Radiometrie. This allows you to benefit from improved performance while minimizing the need for
                        additional costly spare parts.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3 class="accordion-category-heading">General &amp; Technical Questions</h3>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <button class="accordion-header" aria-expanded="false">
                    What materials and thicknesses can your gauges measure?
                    <span class="accordion-icon"></span>
                </button>
                <div class="accordion-content">
                    <p>
                        Our GaugeMaster Plus systems are equipped with various DC X-ray sources suitable for a wide range of materials and thicknesses.
                        The table below outlines the maximum thickness our gauges can measure for both steel and pure aluminum, based on the X-ray source model:
                    </p>
                    <picture>
                        <source srcset="~/images/faq/rsi-mastergauge-applications-table-600.webp?v=1" type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 767px)" />
                        <img src="~/images/faq/rsi-mastergauge-applications-table.png"
                             asp-append-version="true"
                             alt="A table showing the maximum measurable thickness for steel and aluminum based on different X-ray source kilovolt (kV) ratings."
                             class="accordion-image"
                             loading="lazy"
                             width="1200" height="718" />
                    </picture>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <button class="accordion-header" aria-expanded="false">
                    What is X-ray gauging?
                    <span class="accordion-icon"></span>
                </button>
                <div class="accordion-content">
                    <p>
                        X-ray gauging is a non-contact method to measure the thickness of materials like steel and aluminum. It uses a C-frame with an x-ray source
                        in the lower arm and a detector in the upper arm. By measuring how the material absorbs the x-rays, we can determine its thickness with high
                        accuracy and speed.
                    </p>
                    <picture>
                        <source srcset="~/images/faq/rsi-c-frame-illustration-600.webp?v=1" type="image/webp" media="(max-width: 767px)" />
                        <img src="~/images/faq/rsi-c-frame-illustration.jpg"
                             asp-append-version="true"
                             alt="Diagram of a C-Frame Gauge"
                             class="accordion-image"
                             loading="lazy"
                             width="654" height="603" />
                    </picture>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <button class="accordion-header" aria-expanded="false">
                    How do you ensure measurement accuracy over time?
                    <span class="accordion-icon"></span>
                </button>
                <div class="accordion-content">
                    <p>
                        While other manufacturers regulate beam intensity, RSI also tightly regulates beam energy. This ensures excellent long-term stability and maintains
                        accuracy without needing a large number of internal samples. Our proprietary X-ray Spectrum Correction (XSC) technique compensates for the "aging"
                        effect of components, guaranteeing that alloy correction factors do not change over the life of the gauge.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <button class="accordion-header" aria-expanded="false">
                    Why should I choose RSI over other vendors?
                    <span class="accordion-icon"></span>
                </button>
                <div class="accordion-content">
                    <p>
                        RSI is the industry leader in DMC and Radiometrie support with over 200 years of combined gauging experience. Our products are Made in the USA,
                        and we provide fast, responsive on-site service from our multiple US-based Service Centers, backed by a 24/7 emergency hotline.
                        At RSI, the customer is #1.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

